

 **************  /usr/ipsc/examples/nx_c/fp_excp_hand/README  *****************


iPSC Floating Point Exception Handling for C programmers

When running C programs on the nodes, floating point exceptions, normally 
do not occur because the interrupt is masked.  If you want this interrupt to 
occur you must load the 80287 with a different control word mask. You can find 
an example of a node program that loads the control word in node.c.  This C main
program calls ldcw87, the actual routine that loads the control word.  The 
routine ldcw87 is in written in assembly and can be found in ldcw87.asm.  When 
the control word is unmasked and an exception occurs the default NX floating 
point exception handler performs the proper IEEE math corrections.

Similarly, When running C programs on the host floating point exceptions, 
normally do not occur because the interrupt is masked.  If you want this 
interrupt to occur, you must load the 80287 with a different control word mask.
Also XENIX must be informed to use an IEEE exception handler rather than the 
default exception handler.  This is done with a call to "signal" documented in 
the "C Library Guide".  An example of a host program that loads the control word
and calls "signal" can be found in the /usr/ipsc/examples/nx_c/fp_eh/host.c.
Also in this directory you will find a IEEE floating point exception
handler, the same one that is used at default on the nodes and for
FORTRAN host programs.

The purpose of the host and node program examples is to demonstrate  how
floating point errors are corrected.  Both node.c and host.c set the control 
word, call "signal" and generate floating point errors.  The exception 
handlers correct the errors and the programs continue as if the errors had 
never occurred.  To use these files, please copy them into your own working 
directory.

  
This directory contains the following programs:

     1.  Source code for test programs, called node.c and host.c.
         "Node" runs on a node and "host" runs on the host.  The node 
 	 program puts its output in SYSLOG, and does not require a 
	 host program.  The host program writes results to the 
	 screen.  To build the executable programs
	 type:  make all.

     2.  Source for dhex, which prints floating point numbers in 
	 hexadecimal format with reasonable byte order.

     3.  Source for fpeh, used by the host example to "install" the 
	 exception handler on XENIX (calls signal and ldcw87).

     4.  ASM 286 source code for the exception handler (eh287n.asm). 

     5.  ASM 286 source code to generate a subroutine to execute a fldcw 
         (load control word) to the 287 (ldcw87.asm).
          
     6.  A makefile to generate the test program, and link it in with the 
         floating point exception handler. You may use this makefile as an 
         example of how to link your application in with the exception 
         handler.

To execute the example on the host just type:

	host

To execute the example on the node type:

	getcube
	load -c 0
	load node   - results are sent to the logfile



TECHNICAL NOTES:

As you know, the Intel 8087 was designed, and first shipments made, before
the IEEE floating point standard was finally adopted.  The 8087, and hence
the 80287 used in the iPSC, conforms to draft 8 of the standard, rather than
to the final, official, draft 10.  The primary difference between the two
drafts concerns the handling of denormal numbers.  For 64-bit arithmetic
(Fortran double precision), these are floating point numbers in the range
from 2.0**(-1022) to 2.0**(-1074), or roughly 2.22E-308 to 4.94E-324.
The difficulty, and controversy, occurs when denormal numbers are involved
in arithmetic operations that yield results in the normal range, greater
than 2.0**(-1022).  We call such results "promoted denormals".  For example:

            X = 1.0E-305
            Y = 1.0E+10
            Z = X/Y
            A = (X/Y)*Y
            B = 1.0E0 + X/Y

The quantity Z, whose value is 1.0E-315, is a denormal number.  It is
generated correctly by  Fortran, running on any 8087 machine, with 
no special exception handling.  No trouble so far.  The difficulties 
occur with the next two statements, both of which produce "promoted 
denormals".  The quantity A should be equal to X, except that several 
bits of accuracy have been lost because the intermediate denormal result 
is represented with less relative precision.  Should the user be warned 
of this loss of accuracy?  The value stored in B should be exactly 1.0 
since X/Y is numerically negligible compared to 1.0.  Should the warning 
that might be expected for A also be generated for B?

Draft 8 provides for a "warning mode" to signal the promotion of denormals.
But it was judged to be of such esoteric utility that draft 10 makes no 
mention of warning mode.  The 8087 allows for software implementation of 
warning mode, but, as far as we know, no such software has ever been written.

The 8087 produces a NaN, a special bit pattern signifying "Not a Number",
for a promoted denormal.  If the last bit of the 8087 control word is on,
then NaN's propagate through subsequent arithmetic operations, producing
further NaN's.  In this case, both A and B would be NaN's.  It might be
argued that such a result is reasonable for A, but we think that it is hard
to justify for B.  In this case, any attempt to store a NaN, or to do 
arithmetic involving a NaN, is trapped and declared illegal.  The result 
is Floating Point Exception, a dead program, and little helpful 
traceback information.

Fortunately, we can now do better than either of these cases.  The exception
handler in this directory allows the generation of a result close
to X for A, an exact 1.0 for B, and continued execution of any subsequent
statements.


HOST / NODE PROGRAM DIFFERENCES:

Installing a floating point exception handler requires different steps 
for node and host programs.  If you study the examples in this directory you
will notice these different. 


NODE PROGRAMS:

main()
{
   .
/* call to ldcw87 - loads different mask */
   cdum=ldcw87(cw); 
   .
}




HOST PROGRAMS:

main()
{
   .
call to fpeh 
   .
}

fpeh()
{
   .
/* call to ldcw87 - loads control word                       */
/* call to signal - tells XENIX to call sig_fpe for signal 8 */
  ldcw87(0x13bc);
  signal(SIGFPE,sig_fpe);
   .
}

sig_fpe()
{
   .
/* call ieee_handler - actual call to exception handler      */ 
/* call to signal - tells XENIX to call sig_fpe for signal 8 */
  ieee_handler();
  signal(SIGFPE,sig_fpe);
   .
}
